<DOC><DOCNO> AP880627-0039 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 0314EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i PM-Airbus-Glance     06-27 0216</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Airbus-Glance,0226</SECOND><HEAD>Airbus At A Glance</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-France-Crash, Bjt</HEAD><HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD><TEXT>   Here are some facts on the Airbus A320, the twin-engine jetlinerthat crashed in eastern France on Sunday:</TEXT><TEXT>   MANUFACTURER: Airbus Industrie, a Toulouse, France-basedEuropean consortium. First test-flown on Feb. 22, 1987, the planewas certified on Feb. 26.</TEXT><TEXT>   CAPACITY: Normally seats 150 passengers but can carry up to 179.Carries a crew of two on the flight deck, with one (optionally two)additional crew members. Four flight attendants.</TEXT><TEXT>   DIMENSIONS: A 111-foot wingspan, overall length of 123 feet andheight of 38 feet. The wheelbase is 41 feet. Passenger doors arefront and aft on the port side, with two emergency exits over wingson both sides.</TEXT><TEXT>   SPECIAL FACTS: Has a range of about 3,700 miles and consumes 40percent less fuel than similar two or three engine jets.   It is the first civilian airliner equipped with a fullycomputerized flight-control system the manufacturer says permitssafer, electronically controlled flight. Instead of the old controlcolumn in front of the pilot, there is a ``pistol-grip'' side sticklinked to five computers that modify and relay the pilot'sdirections to wing and tail flaps.   Airbus Industrie has 500 orders to purchase the craft, whichcost about $60 million each.</TEXT></DOC>